<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-057-123 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 316 797</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 19 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Radio-linked network to be offered to airlines. (Ericsson GE,Speedwing Mobile Communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ericsson-G.E. Mobile Data Inc. (Services)Speedwing Mobile Communications (Services).andO;Topic:     Wireless NetworksReservation SystemsAirline IndustryWide area networksRadio Communication.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>RADIO-LINKED NETWORK TO BE OFFERED TO AIRLINES 09/19/91 PARAMUS, NEW JERSEY,U.S.A., 1991 SEP 19 (NB) -- Ericsson GE and Speedwing Mobile Communications,a division of British Airways, will jointly market a mobile data system,which operates via radio waves, to the global airline industry.andP;  The systemwill link fueling crews, baggage handlers, caterers, and reservation agentsto airline mainframes using the Mobitex radio data system developed inSweden.andP;  The system would replace the phone links now used.andM;Ram Mobile offers in a few U.S.andP;  cities a Mobitex system to truckingandM;firms and others with large, dispersed workforces, in competition with Ardis,a joint venture between Motorola and IBM.andP;  Mobitex networks are alsooperating in Canada, Sweden, Finland, and Norway.andM;Speedwing has developed a software interface called Ramsgate which will allowthe users to access applications on the mainframes.andP;  Warren Armstrong,managing director for Speedwing, noted that &quot;delays in the airline industryare measured in thousands of dollars per minute.&quot;andM;Ericsson GE will provide Speedwing with vehicle-mounted radio modems as wellas future portable products which will allow the mobile data terminals tocommunicate with the Mobitex network.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19910918/Press Contact: Ericsson, Kathy Egan, 212/685-4030)</TEXT></DOC>